About Ahmedabad

Ahmedabad, in western India, is the largest city in the state of Gujarat. The Sabarmati River runs through its center. On the western bank is the Gandhi Ashram at Sabarmati, which displays the spiritual leader’s living quarters and artifacts. Across the river, the Calico Museum of Textiles, once a cloth merchant's mansion, has a significant collection of antique and modern fabrics.

Frequently asked questions about flying to Ahmedabad

When should you visit Ahmedabad?
Peak travel is Dec–Feb, the mildest and driest part of the year. Mar–Jun is very hot, when the weather also becomes increasingly humid and breezy ahead of the monsoon. Wet season rainfall peaks Jul–Aug. An International Kite Festival (Jan) forms part of the Hindu celebrations for Uttarayan. Navratri (varies Sep/Oct), or "nine nights", is celebrated with colorful traditional dance and garba music. The Hindu festivals of Rath Yatra (varies Jun/Jul) and Diwali (varies Oct/Nov) are also popular with visitors.
What is the best airport to fly into Ahmedabad?
Ahmedabad is served by only one major airport: Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel International Airport, 7 km away from the city center.
